Claude Fable 5 on 2026-07-17 at ~16:35: The card is made: `assets/bb-card-whatsapp.png` —1000×1000, transparent, the same rig as `bb-card.png` but with 'jonatanbb.xyz' in full gold on the fourth-quadrant arc and no trace of 'WILLING TO WORK'— plus a white-flattened companion, `assets/bb-card-whatsapp-white.png`, which is the one I'd actually upload to WhatsApp.

**The digging.** The original card's method is recorded in iteration26's interaction file (the capture rig itself was scratch work, so I rebuilt it): a browser capture of the live source with the random scatter suppressed, the i-dot parked far off-page (it's the pulse root, so the ignition still plays and settles into the true rest state), the reflective text layer dropped, the page chrome hidden, the ground made transparent, and a square clip around the annulus with a pad of 30% of the outer radius —1000×1000, alpha kept.

**The modification.** I replayed that rig on a scratch copy of `sources/current` (the repo is untouched) with the ring-message machinery itself carrying the new text, so it's the site's own Inter bold, laid letter-by-letter along the mid-radius arc exactly like the carved message: `STR` set to `jonatanbb.xyz`, the string centre moved to your 7π/4 (the canvas y-axis points down, so that's canvas π/4 —the middle of the bottom-right quarter, the arc the centre point leaves dark at rest), the π/5 'WORK' rotation zeroed, the font fraction raised 50% (0.35 → 0.525 of the ring thickness), and every letter forced to full heat so the whole string sits at the official gold #fad02a instead of reading the light on its arc. The rest state came out identical to bb-card's —same lit bands, same b-faces, same centre glow— with the domain reading left-to-right up the arc, letter tops toward the centre.

**The white variant.** WhatsApp converts uploads to JPEG and drops the alpha —on many clients the transparent ground lands on black, which would swallow the annulus. So the store also carries the same card flattened onto white (the site's day ground). Use the white one for the profile photo; the transparent one is there as the faithful master if you ever want the mark on something else.
